🔥 Today’s Concepts

1️⃣ ER Model (Entity Relationship Model)
2️⃣ Cardinality (1:1, 1:M, M:N)

1️⃣ ER Model
Big Idea

Before creating tables, we first model the real world.

That model is called ER Model.

ER Model = Blueprint of database

Think of it like building a house:

First blueprint
Then construction

Same with databases.

Three Main Parts
🔹 Entity

An Entity is an object we store data about.

Examples:

Student
Course
Teacher
Mental Model 🧠
Entity = Noun

If it feels like a “thing”, likely entity.

🔹 Attributes

Attributes are properties of entity.

Student entity:

Roll number
Name
Branch

Like Python dictionary:

student = {
 "id":1,
 "name":"Akshay",
 "branch":"CSE"
}

Keys are attributes.

🔹 Relationship

How entities connect.

Example:

Student enrolls in Course

That is relationship.

Visual Idea
Student ---- enrolls ---- Course
Memory Trick
Entity = thing

Attribute = property

Relationship = connection
Real Example

Entities:

Student
Course

Attributes:

Student:

student_id
name

Course:

course_id
course_name

Relationship:

Student enrolls in Course

Why ER Model Matters

✔ Converts business idea into DB design
✔ Avoids bad schemas
✔ Frequently asked in interviews

2️⃣ Cardinality

Now we ask:

👉 How many entities relate to how many?

That is cardinality.

🔹 One-to-One (1:1)

One record matches one record.

Example:

Person ↔ Passport

One person → one passport
🔹 One-to-Many (1:M)

Most common.

Example:

Department → Many Students

One department
Many students

CSE has many students.

🔹 Many-to-Many (M:N)

Example:

Students ↔ Courses

One student takes many courses

One course has many students

Many-to-many.

How Databases Handle Many-to-Many

Using junction table:

Enrollment

student_id	course_id

Solved.

Python Mental Model 🧠

One-to-many:

department = {
 "CSE":["Akshay","Rahul"]
}

Many-to-many:

enrollments = [
 {"student":1,"course":101},
 {"student":1,"course":102}
]
Easy Memory Trick
1:1  → one-one

1:M → one-many

M:N → many-many
🔥 Placement Insight

Very common questions:

Q1: Difference entity vs attribute?

Entity = object

Attribute = property of object

Q2: Most common relationship?

👉 One-to-many

Q3: How represent many-to-many in relational DB?

👉 Use junction table.

